===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''[[verray#Middle English|verray, verrai]]'' "true" (compare Modern {{en}}: ''[[verily]]'') from {{etyl|fro}} ''[[verai#Old French|verai]]'' "true" (Modern {{fr}}: ''[[vrai#French|vrai]]'' "true") from {{etyl|VL.}} ''*veracus'' from {{etyl|la}} ''[[verax]]'' "true" from {{proto|Indo-European|wēr-|true, benevolent|lang=en}}. Akin to {{etyl|ang|-}} ''[[wær#Old English|wǣr]]'' "true, correct", {{etyl|osx|-}} ''[[war#Old Saxon|wār]]'' "true", {{etyl|odt|-}} ''[[war#Old Dutch|wār]]'' "true" ({{etyl|nl|-}} ''[[waar#Dutch|waar]]'' "true"), {{etyl|goh|-}} ''[[war#Old High German|wār]]'' "true" ({{etyl|de|-}} ''[[wahr#German|wahr]]'' "true"). Displaced native {{enm}} ''[[sore#Middle English|sar, sore]]'' "very" (from {{ang}} ''[[sar#Old English|sār]]'' "grievous, extreme"), {{enm}} ''[[wel#Middle English|wel]]'' "very" (from {{ang}} ''[[wel#Old English|wel]]'' "well, very").

